Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and attach handlers to all six events:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Created     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🟢 Created");
        window.Activated   += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🟢 Activated");
        window.Deactivated += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🟡 Deactivated");
        window.Stopped     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🔴 Stopped");
        window.Resumed     += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("🔵 Resumed");
        window.Destroying  += (s, e) => Debug.WriteLine("⚫ Destroying");

        return window;
    }
}
```

**Key things to watch for in your logs:**

| Transition | What you'll see |
|---|---|
| First launch | `Created` → `Activated` (no `Resumed`) |
| User switches away | `Deactivated` → `Stopped` |
| User returns | `Resumed` → `Activated` |
| Notification shade / dialog | `Deactivated` only (no `Stopped`) |
| Android back button | May jump straight to `Destroying`, skipping `Stopped` |

**Tip:** If you also want the raw **platform-native** callbacks, add `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
{
#if ANDROID
    events.AddAndroid(a => a
        .OnCreate((act, b) => Debug.WriteLine("Android OnCreate"))
        .OnResume(act    => Debug.WriteLine("Android OnResume"))
        .OnPause(act     => Debug.WriteLine("Android OnPause"))
        .OnStop(act      => Debug.WriteLine("Android OnStop"))
        .OnDestroy(act   => Debug.WriteLine("Android OnDestroy")));
#elif IOS || MACCATALYST
    events.AddiOS(ios => ios
        .DidBecomeActive(a  => Debug.WriteLine("iOS DidBecomeActive"))
        .WillResignActive(a => Debug.WriteLine("iOS WillResignActive"))
        .DidEnterBackground(a   => Debug.WriteLine("iOS DidEnterBackground"))
        .WillEnterForeground(a  => Debug.WriteLine("iOS WillEnterForeground")));
#endif
});
```

This lets you correlate the cross-platform events with their native counterparts in the debug output.
